 writing:

All of that noted, the combination of Google and Microsoft=E2=80=99s result=
s make Amazon=E2=80=99s earnings tomorrow very interesting indeed. If AWS l=
ooks like Google than it suggests that Microsoft has a meaningful advantage=
 in AI infrastructure; if AWS is done talking about optimizations and ready=
 to talk about realized AI growth then Google=E2=80=99s results will deserv=
e even more scrutiny.

Jassy spent a lot of time talking about generative AI, but when asked speci=
fically, =E2=80=9CHow should we think about the timing, just to drive some =
tangible monetization there?=E2=80=9D, CFO Brian Olsavsky replied:

What I would tell you is that we have been surprised at the pace of growth =
in generative AI. Our generative AI business is growing very, very quickly,=
 as I mentioned earlier. And almost by any measure, it=E2=80=99s a pretty s=
ignificant business for us already. And yet I would also say that companies=
 are still in the relatively early stages.

What he didn=E2=80=99t provide was a number; I think it=E2=80=99s safe to s=
ay that it is a lot less than Microsoft=E2=80=99s claim that AI is driving =
an incremental three points of growth. Still, at least AWS stabilized overa=
ll, matching last quarter=E2=80=99s 12% growth rate, off of the largest bas=
e of the three major providers; that means that only Google=E2=80=99s growt=
h meaningfully declined.

That noted, Jassy emphasized that this is early days for AI, and that =E2=
=80=9Ccustomers want to bring the models to their data, not the other way a=
round=E2=80=9D; of course this observation is self-serving, but it also str=
ikes me as correct. To take things back to Google, though, this only height=
ens concerns that its core cloud business is slowing. Yes, it=E2=80=99s AI =
offerings may be compelling, but it is a taller order to get companies to s=
witch for your AI offerings than to simply get them to start using your off=
erings with data you already host. Moreover, that slowing may be in part du=
e to AI; Doug O=E2=80=99Laughlin noted on Fabricated Knowledge ( https://ww=
w.fabricatedknowledge.com/p/weekly-earnings-asml-lrcx-tsmc-nod ) in the con=
text of reviewing TSMC=E2=80=99s earnings:

They called out further strength in HPC, which grew 6% QoQ. We know that Nv=
idia is driving a large part of this, and I want to highlight the disparity=
 between their results and Nvidia=E2=80=99s guide. Nvidia guided their outl=
ook to grow 16% revenue quarter over quarter, and while they are not the en=
tirety of HPC, it means that the rest of HPC revenue declined quarter over =
quarter. There is a 1-month mismatch, but this likely means that data cente=
r cannibalization is very real, and this is the proof. Watch out, AMD.

AMD reports later today, but this context matters for the cloud providers t=
oo: if new growth increasingly comes from AI then it is going to be to the =
advantage of companies that already have the biggest cloud businesses, whic=
h means AWS, then Azure, with Google Cloud Platform only just barely profit=
able. Again, these are very early days, but this is something that bears wa=
tching.

The Logistics Virtuous Cycle
----------------------------

While Jassy spent a lot of time on generative AI, he opened his prepared re=
marks by talking about Amazon=E2=80=99s logistics overhaul:

I=E2=80=99ll start with our stores business. Our move earlier this year fro=
m a single national fulfillment network in the U.S. to 8 distinct regions r=
epresented one of the most significant changes to our fulfillment network i=
n our history. This change has gone more smoothly and made more impact than=
 we optimistically expected. And you can see the benefits in many forms. Re=
gional fulfillment clusters with higher local in-stock levels and optimized=
 connections between fulfillment centers and delivery stations mean shorter=
 distances and fewer touches to get items to customers.

Shorter travel distances and fewer touches mean lower cost to serve. But pe=
rhaps most importantly, shorter distances and fewer touches mean that custo=
mers are getting their shipments faster. We remain on pace to deliver the f=
astest delivery speeds for Prime customers in our 29-year history. And as I=
 talked about last quarter, we know how important speed of delivery is to c=
ustomer satisfaction and buying behavior. A good example is the significant=
 growth we=E2=80=99re seeing in consumables and everyday essentials. When c=
ustomers are getting items as quickly and conveniently as they are now from=
 Amazon, they=E2=80=99re going to consider us more frequently for more of t=
heir shopping needs.

As we=E2=80=99ve shared the last few quarters, we=E2=80=99ve re-evaluated e=
very part of our fulfillment network over the last year. The first substant=
ial rearchitecture centered on the regionalization change. We obviously lik=
e the results but don=E2=80=99t think we fully realize all the benefits yet=
 and we continue to make steady improvements in fine-tuning the placement a=
lgorithms to enable even more in-region fulfillment and to further increase=
 consolidation into fewer shipments. We=E2=80=99ve also identified several =
substantial changes to our inbound processes that we believe could have a s=
ignificant impact on our cost to serve and speed of delivery. We have a lon=
g way before being out of ideas to improve cost and speed. The team is real=
ly humming on this and I=E2=80=99m proud of the way they=E2=80=99re inventi=
ng and executing together.

Multiple regions with simpler distribution resulting in faster speeds and l=
ower prices may sound like an obvious win, but it is the sort of change tha=
t is only possible because of massive volume and, most importantly, massive=
 investment.

First off, this is the sort of risk-taking that should be rewarded, not pun=
ished by regulators ( https://stratechery.com/2023/ftc-sues-amazon-fba-and-=
prime-pricing-punishment/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cm=
F0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVy=
