cle.

Amazon Aggregator Ads
---------------------

It=E2=80=99s more than that, though: increased speed driving more purchases=
 on Amazon also drives Amazon=E2=80=99s advertising business. Jassy explain=
ed in response to a question about the ad business, which grew 25% year-ove=
r-year:

I think on the ad front, well, there=E2=80=99s a lot I=E2=80=99m excited ab=
out on the ad side as well. I think that it=E2=80=99s interesting what=E2=
=80=99s happened in our ads business as if you look around the industry, mo=
st advertising-heavy companies have struggled growth-wise as the economy ha=
s been difficult. And while we see companies being more cautious on the ad =
side and the top-of-funnel products, things like display and a little bit o=
f video, we=E2=80=99re still seeing a lot of strength in the lower-funnel a=
d products like sponsored products. And I think in these types of economies=
, we have fared pretty well in part because we have a number of owned and o=
perated properties that have very large volumes that advertisers and brands=
 want to get in front of. Even in a harder economy, there=E2=80=99s going t=
o be a lot of e-commerce purchasing. So people want to be in front of our c=
ustomers in our marketplace.

Owned-and-operated properties that command customer attention =E2=80=94 i.e=
. demand =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the characteristic of an Aggregator, and adverti=
sing has always been the most compelling Aggregator business model; it=E2=
=80=99s the chief characteristic of what I called the Super Aggregators ( h=
ttps://stratechery.com/2017/the-super-aggregators-and-the-russians/?access_=
token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSI=
